Senior Keelan Durham
Keelan is this years‚Äô Valedictorian. He is not taking Oxbow classes at this time because he has been going to school in Norway. He is part of student council as well as the National Honors Society. Keelan ran on our varsity cross country and track teams but his passion lies in nordic skiing. Last year he skied in the US Ski and Snowboard Junior National Cross Country Championship in Anchorage, Alaska, where he skied as a member of the New England Team and placed 7th in the classic sprint. He has been working on his family‚Äôs farm while keeping up with his school work. Keelan plans to go to Williams College in the fall. You‚Äôre future‚Äôs looking bright, we are proud of you Keelan.

Oxbow High School Highlight
Senior Lauren Wright
Lauren is currently enrolled in the Cosmetology program at River Bend. She is part of Oxbow‚Äôs NHS and River Bend‚Äôs NTHS as well as student leadership and youth-adult continuous improvement team at River Bend.
Before the pandemic Lauren was working 60 hours a week between two jobs to help save for college. She works at Lake Morey Resort and Supercuts. She is currently paying all of her own bills because she is living on her own in an apartment. She was part of Oxbow‚Äôs varsity basketball team. Lauren‚Äôs plans after graduation is to move to Knoxville, TN and attend Paul Mitchell the School of Knoxville for cosmetology beginning in September. ‚ÄúI am very excited for a fresh start, and to be so close to reaching my dream. It hasn‚Äôt been easy, but I gained a lot of perseverance over the years and will keep chasing every dream.‚Äù says Lauren. You will do amazing things Lauren, chase those dreams!

Here is a video of 8th grader Lizzie Vaughan and her final project for 8th grade science.
In this activity, they had to design, build, test and improve (if necessary) a roller coaster track. Their designs
had the following criteria:
‚Ä¢ must be exactly 12 feet long.
‚Ä¢ must have at least one hill in addition to the ‚Äúinitial drop.‚Äù
‚Ä¢ Your cart is a marble or other small ball. The marble must make it to the end of the track.
‚Ä¢ You can use tape, books and other objects to create hills, loops, twists, turns, etc. in your track.
‚Ä¢ You will have the opportunity to improve and retest your design ONE time.
GREAT WORK LIZZIE!

Grab N' Go program changing soon...

Did you hear we are transitioning soon to once a week bulk deliveries on Wednesdays coming out of the BES Food Hub? You will see our regular two day deliveries Wed 6/10, Friday 6/12, & Monday 6/15 and then starting Wednesday 6/17 you will only see us once a week with 7 days worth of breakfasts and lunches and a gallon of milk each. As a bonus, it all comes in a colorful reusable shopping bag that you get to keep! Watch for details on which areas we will be able to service and a google survey to sign up for a drop every week until mid August! Please sign up...we want to help feed you!

Please sign up using the attached link: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1EngHPh_QSpIP1awNo2NtHcvbnE_vxVHgohvjw2S9PJI/edit?usp=sharing

For updates and/or changes to the program - please follow the Bradford Elementary School Facebook page.

ATTENTION SENIORS:
Have some takeout on VSAC

Class of 2020! VSAC wants to buy a takeout meal for graduating seniors.

Every Friday from now until June 26, VSAC will randomly pick 5 seniors to get a $50 takeout meal from your favorite local restaurant or food business. Here‚Äôs what you do: Post a photo with the hashtag #VSACDelivers and tag @802VSAC, and VSAC will choose 5 winners every Friday at 4:30 and be in contact with you about what you want to eat!

You‚Äôll also receive a $50 Gift of College card, courtesy of Vermont‚Äôs 529 savings plan administered by VSAC. And everyone who posts a photo is entered into a drawing for $529 in the Vermont Higher Education Investment Plan. Want more information? Email haskell@vsac.org.

-Ms. Wheeler

Amber has been balancing her Riverbend Cosmetology class as well as Oxbow classes during this remote learning time all while working 32 hours a week. post_text:
Jessica Parent is this year‚Äôs Oxbow High School Salutatorian. She is the daughter of David Parent of East Corinth, VT. Jessica has always chosen courses that were challenging for her both academically and intellectually. She opted for courses that interested her, teachers who piqued her curiosity, and always pushed herself to excel in everything she tried. Her
determination, drive, and work ethic propel her to delve deeper into her learning. This dedication is what teachers see and appreciate in the classroom every day. In addition to
school Jessica has held a part-time job as a housekeeper at a hotel. She has worked nights, weekends, and summers all throughout high school. This experience has not only helped her family but taught her the important skills of money management, responsibility, reliability, attention to detail, and perseverance. Jessica will be attending the Northern Vermont University in Lyndon, VT in the fall where she will continue to explore a variety of academic areas.

Congratulations Jessie, we are proud of you!!!!!

shared_text:
Cassie Marie was live.
March 26 at 10:38 AM ¬∑

Today, we are going to a demo using Newton's Laws of Motion!

**UPDATE!** So for some reason, the video stopped recording before I was done - ugh! So here's a review of the mini lesson at the end:

1. The egg has more inertia than the toilet paper roll because it has more mass. Therefore, it is more difficult to move and takes more force to move.
2. When you apply a force to the plastic lid, it moves the lid as well as the toilet paper roll because it has less inertia (an object at rest stays at rest unless acted upon by an outside force! Newton's First Law!)
3. Because the egg has more inertia, it did not travel with the lid and TP roll, so it stayed at rest UNTIL gravity pulled it down into the water.
4. Newton's First Law is also called the Law of Inertia.

There's Newton's First Law in action!

#sciencewithsaikin

post_text:
Written by a wise and caring teacher...

Hey Hey Everyone!! Hear this please... the expectation for kids learning at home CANNOT be the same as what they were expected to do in the school setting!! There are soo many factors that are playing into them not keeping the same exact routine and schedule! Ease into it! This is just as new to them as it is for you and they will need some time to adjust to putting forth a different mental focus at home and that's ok! Honestly, as teachers, we over-plan all the time and this situation probably isn't all that different. Ask questions of us, clarify expectations, but please please don't fight with your children about the work! Their mental health is a priority right now as their precious world has been shifted quickly and dramatically! There is not a teacher out there that doesn't want to help with what they've sent home so please reach out to them if you need to! We can and will do this together! Relax, take a deep breath, and just say, "we'll try again tomorrow!" üôåüíû

post_text:
The results are in!! The National Geographic Society names Isibeal Bohan, 7th grader at OHS, as one of the semifinalists eligible to compete in the 2020 National Geographic GeoBee State Competition. The contest will be held at the Equinox Spa and Resort in Manchester, VT on March 27th. To make it to the semifinals Isibeal won two rounds of competition here at Oxbow. She beat 26 other 7th graders to win the preliminary GeoBee, then two other kids in the finals. She then successfully completed a 70 question qualifying test online to qualify for the State competition. Isibeal is one of the 100 qualified for the State championship competition. Winners will receive a medal, $1,000 in cash and other prizes as well as a trip to Washington, D.C., to represent VT in the National Championship where they will compete for additional cash awards and college scholarships. The 2020 National Championship will take place May 18-21, 2020, at the National Geographic headquarters.

Visit www.natgeobee.org for more information on the National Geographic GeoBee.

post_text:
Good Afternoon,
We can keep our students healthy during this flu season by following these very important steps:
Wash their backpacks, jackets and other clothing items that they wear often.
Keep them home if they are sick, or have been sick within the last 24 hours.
Remind them to wash their hands on a regular basis, and cough/sneeze into their elbows.

We will continue to wipe down surfaces of frequent contact, such as desks, keyboards, doorknobs...

STUDENTS WHO BECOME ILL WHILE AT SCHOOL WILL BE REQUIRED TO SEE THE NURSE BEFORE BEING RELEASED.

Thank you for your cooperation. Stay healthy.
Ms. Wheeler

post_text: Yesterday we had a callback assembly where guest speaker Molly Thompson came in to speak to students about empathy and kindness. Molly went to Hartland Elementary school and then Woodstock High School, she is now currently at Saint Michael‚Äôs College in Colchester, VT where she is studying to become a college professor. Molly was born with Pfeiffer Syndrome, a disorder characterized by the prefusion of certain skull bones, along with a variety of other health issues. She talked to students about what it is like to have a disability and persevere. Molly is working to advocate for those who are different or have disabilities. She talked to the students about being kind, asking appropriate questions and be respectful to those who are different. Thank you Molly for coming to OHS and telling your story.

post_text: Mrs. Eastman‚Äôs middle school Wellness class is working on a Nutrition unit where they learned how to read nutrition facts in order to eat three balanced meals a day and make healthy food choices. The group project was for students to make a healthy snack. Students are constantly on the go and the goal was to find a snack that could be made quick and easy but also healthy. The students got into groups and found a healthy snack recipe they wanted to make. On Wednesday they went into the maker space kitchen and made their healthy snacks. Some of the snacks they made were; fruit smoothies, healthy fruit pastry, fruit popsicles, healthier version of ramen noodles, and banana with peanut butter.

‚ÄúDear VT Supports team,

Our team at Resolute Support headquarters, Strategic Communication and Public Affairs division, would like to thank you for your generous holiday packages. We are stationed in Kabul, Afghanistan and support the US Forces-Afghanistan mission, as well as the NATO mission. Your gifts arrived about a week before Christmas and were greatly appreciated by the entire team, some of which were not able to be in the picture. We shared them within our division to include our two NATO partners from Great Britain.

Thank you for thinking of the service men and women, both uniformed and civilian, who are serving our country away from their homes and loved ones during this special time of year.

Respectfully,

Chief of Staff, Public Affairs

post_text: Yesterday Oxbow participated in a card making event. The auditorium turned into our workshop and students and staff came in throughout the day to make cards for our troops. We assembled over 1000 cards that will be sent to deployed military personnel along with care packages put together by the organization called VT Supports. There were various stations set up; card decorating, message writing, card signing and envelop stuffing. This was a great event for Oxbow to be part of. Thank you to those who helped organize this event for OHS!!!!

post_text: Every year Oxbow's faculty and staff participate in "Share the Bounty" during the weeks leading up to Thanksgiving. Each year we gather together items to complete a Thanksgiving meal, choose a family to receive this meal and the staff here at OHS bring in the items for the meal. This year we put together enough meals for eight families. This has been an Oxbow tradition for years and we are so happy to support our community during the holidays.

post_text:
Ms. Jones 7th grade class is studying climate control. Their task was to see how much exhaust came out of three different types of vehicles using mathematical calculations.
The students used a bus, a 1998 Chevy Blazer and a 2018 Honda CRV to determine how much exhaust came out as the vehicle started up. They found the bus had the most exhaust and the blazer had the least amount of exhaust except it smelled terrible.
This morning the 7th grade class stood outside of OHS with pencil and paper to determine how many people came into school in a vehicle vs. a bus. Their next task is to compare rates of the exhaust expended from this mornings commute to school.

post_text:
Yesterday we got to meet Chris Waddell!
Chris went to Middlebury College where he had a skiing accident at age 20 that left him paralyzed from the waist down. He learned to overcome obstacles he never thought he would have to face. He went back to college after the accident and later won 12 Winter Paralympic medals and three Summer Paralympic medals. He also won nine World Championship medals. In 2009 he became the first nearly unassisted paraplegic to summit Mt. Kilimanjaro. Chris has accomplished many amazing events throughout his life.
THANK YOU CHRIS, your message was powerful and inspiring.

A message from our Athletic Director- Derek Cipriano:
There will be a MANDATORY fall sports information meeting for all high school student-athletes and their families, on August 8th at 6:00 in the gym.
Middle school families are more than welcome to attend this evening, but it is not required.
Our online registration system, FormReleaf is updated and ready to go. Please take the time to register your child for the sport they are participating in. Please also make sure that your child has an updated physical, completed within the last two years, on file with the school. Without an updated physical and online registration, students will be unable to participate.

-Football season begins on August 12th.
-High school soccer and Cross Country begins on August 15th.
-Middle school sports begin on the second day of school, August 29th.

Any questions contact:
Derek Cipriano
Director of Athletics and Activities
dcipriano@oxbowhs.org
802-222-5214 ex. 152

The Oxbow Community Scholarship For Excellence (OCSE) is in need of new board members for the following volunteer positions: Chairperson, Secretary, 2 Community Members (business owners or parents or other interested parties), 2 Oxbow Employees. The board is in charge of raising between $10,000 and $15,000 annually to be given to graduating seniors who have enrolled in the program and meets approximately 5 times throughout the school year. These positions will remain open until filled.

If you are interested in any of these positions please contact Lomond Richardson at lrichardson@oxbowhs.org

Patrick Ross Music Festival
This year it will be June 28 - 30 at Harvest Moon orchard 5449 Main Street, Newbury, VT.

The proceeds go towards music scholarships for those who show proficiency in music but can't afford next level coaching.

This year we will be featuring a handful of local young talent as part of the young musicians showcase. It's a great opportunity for both young musician to gain performance experience and for kids in the audience to be inspired by the watching peers rise to the challenge.

Admission is free for anyone 15 years old or younger with an accompanying paid adult.

Check out the flyer/website: http://patrickrossmusic.com/

Today, the National Honor Society as well as other Oxbow students/staff are sponsoring a food-packaging event here at Oxbow from lunchtime until the end of the day.
It's a pretty big deal: we will be packaging over 30,000 individual meals that will go overseas to feed hungry people.
It's one of the biggest things that NHS and Oxbow has ever done. It was Tim Hodges's idea (OHS senior and member of NHS), with the help from a grant from the Byrne Foundation.

Over 100 students and staff members will be packaging food from noon until the end of the day.

Oxbow will help, Rise Against Hunger!
https://www.riseagainsthunger.org/

Haverhill Herald with Twin State Times at Oxbow High School.
Bradford, VT ¬∑ Paid Partnership ¬∑

Free cooking class Tuesday night. Come and have fun cooking with us, this coming Tuesday, May 21st!

Our free cooking class is an evening of exploring several different recipes
that feature seasonal vegetables. The format is simple, we gather, we
divide into cooking groups, we cook, we taste and enjoy!

Who comes to this class? - anyone! We have had participants from 8 years
old to 80 years old, mothers, daughters, fathers, sons and all shapes and
sizes!! Come to one night, or come every month. Please join us!

Starts at 6:00PM and we try to be cleaned up and out the door by 7:30PM.

We meet at* Oxbow High School, Bradford, VT, Family and Consumer Sciences
Room*
(come in the front door, turn left toward the cafeteria, once in the
cafeteria our room is the first door on the left)

Classes are free and open to all. Please call or email to let me know you
are coming. 802-279-6228. Melanie.loschiavo@gmail.com

Sponsored by Hannaford Supermarkets and The Vermont Blueprint for Health.

Oxbow did well on a cold and rainy day at U32 in the MVAC Freshmen/Sophomore Championships on Monday, 5/13. The girls placed 3rd overall out of 13 scoring teams, and had 4 individual first place finishes with sophomore Kelly Daigle in all three throwing events and freshman Esther Sewall in the 100 Meter Dash.

Results may be found here: https://www.athletic.net/TrackAndField/meet/374271/results.

Girls Team Scores
1. U32, 152
2. Northfield, 73
3. Oxbow, 48
(Oxbow and Rivendell boys did not score any points)

Oxbow Point Scorers (top 6)
Kelly Daigle (So): 1st, Shot Put, 35-02
1st, Javelin, 78-10
